          <MovieSection
            key={section.title}
            title={section.title}
            movies={section.movies}
            onSelect={openModal}
          />
        ))}
      </main>
      {/* Modal */}
      {selectedMovie && (
        <Dialog open={isModalOpen} onOpenChange={setIsModalOpen}>
          <DialogTrigger asChild>
            {/* The trigger is handled by MovieSection's button, but we can also use the Dialog's open state directly */}
            {/* We'll render the DialogContent directly */}
          </DialogTrigger>
          <DialogContent className="bg-gray-800 text-white dark:bg-gray-800">
            <MovieModal movie={selectedMovie} onClose={closeModal} />
          </DialogContent>
        </Dialog>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

But we need to handle the DialogTrigger correctly. Usually we wrap the button that opens modal with DialogTrigger. So we can have MovieSection render each card with a "Details" button that is a DialogTrigger. Then we can have a separate MovieModal component that receives the movie and onClose.

Thus we can restructure:

- In MovieSection, each card includes a "Details" button that triggers the modal.

- The modal component is separate and receives the movie and onClose.

Thus we don't need to manage Dialog open state in page; we can let each card's button open the modal via its own trigger.

But we need to ensure we don't open multiple modals simultaneously. We can have a single modal component at top-level that receives selectedMovie and isOpen state.

Thus we can have page maintain selectedMovie and isOpen. Then each card's "Details" button calls openModal(movie). The button is a DialogTrigger that passes the open state.

But DialogTrigger expects a child that toggles open state? Actually Shadcn Dialog uses Radix UI Dialog. The pattern is:

```tsx
<Dialog open={isOpen} onOpenChange={setIsOpen}>
  <DialogTrigger asChild>
    <Button>Open</Button>
  </DialogTrigger>
  <DialogContent>
    <DialogHeader>
      <DialogTitle>Title</DialogTitle>
    </DialogHeader>
    <DialogDescription>...</DialogDescription>
  </DialogContent>
</DialogContent>
</Dialog>
```

Thus we can have a single Dialog component in page, with open state and onOpenChange. The trigger can be the "Details" button inside each card. However we need to ensure that only one trigger is active at a time. If we have multiple DialogTrigger components with same Dialog, they all toggle the same open state. That's okay; clicking any will open the modal, but we need to set selectedMovie accordingly.

Thus we can have page maintain selectedMovie and isOpen. Then each card's "Details" button calls setSelectedMovie(movie) and setIsOpen(true). The DialogTrigger is just the button.

